<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-222-946  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 222 946.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 24 1989 v6 n16 p73(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Spreadsheet sponge. (Lotus Development first quarter earnings)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (earnings).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Product:   Lotus 1-2-3 (Spreadsheet software) (marketing).andO;Topic:     ProfitSalesSpreadsheetsPromotion of ProductCompetitionMarket Penetration.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Spreadsheet SpongeandM;The cost of promoting Lotus Development Corp.'s aging 1-2-3 spreadsheet tooka bite out of the Cambridge, Mass., firm's bottom line.andM;The company reported net income of $5.3 million, or 13 cents a share, onsales of $120 million for its first quarter, which ended April 1.andM;In the same period last year, Lotus reported net income of $18.3 million, or40 cents a share, on sales of $117 million.andM;This year's first-quarter earnings were lower because of ''marketingpromotions targeted at sustaining our market position in spreadsheets,'' saidRobert Schechter, chief financial officer at Lotus.andM;Lotus has suffered in the last year because rivals such as Microsoft Corp.andO;and Borland International Inc. have attacked the Lotus customer base with newproducts.andM;Meanwhile, Lotus has been unable to ship the upgrades to its 1-2-3spreadsheet.andO;</TEXT></DOC>